Flowerhouse Mexico means a lot to me— and this year in Oaxaca was particularly special. Emerson has grown up around these flower “Tías,”coming to Mexico since he was a baby and each year this group of artists has embraced me not simply as the photographer but also as a mother, which is an identity that I want but sometimes struggle to see myself in when my career takes such a leading role. I traveled with him solo not knowing how that would go while I was photographing but he blended seamlessly into the space, pulling apart marigolds for a mandala, alphabetizing name cards, carrying around a dinosaur piñata, painting alibrije— it was a trip that was so important for us to reconnect after the immense time away last season. He kept saying “I’m excited” and I felt the same way. As all of us say on this project each year, we will go anywhere for Pili— thank you for bringing us together my dear friend and to the tremendous designers, helpers and students who made this such a mesmerizing week of making art and honoring and supporting the children of @casadelaamistadmex — no child should ever have cancer, no parent should ever have to receive that news, and I hope that we can collectively help this important cause that affects so many.

I think I’m always rooted in a classic approach to portraiture, but try to find ways to see the world with modern eyes. Art doesn’t have to be new, but it shouldn’t feel stale either. I am headed to Amsterdam next month to see the Vermeer exhibit and love that all these years after his time, getting tickets to that exhibit was like trying to score seats at a Beyoncé concert. Even the masters have some serious draw. I hope someday someone looks at my work like that and thinks— she really had something there.

Thanks @voguemagazine and @overthemoon for the wonderful feature up today from Rei and Matthew’s dreamy wedding in Bali last September. I will never forget that walk through the Frangipani trees.

@beaniefeldstein gave quite possibly my favorite description anyone has ever given about my photography: 

"She insisted that we go to an old shed far out on the property. Stephanie, one of the owners of Cedar Lakes, was horrified she wanted to shoot it! We were all laughing. But Corbin can see things we mortals cannot and this series of photos in front of that shed hold our hearts”

Sometimes I think photographs end up having a lot of noise in them. And I just like things quiet. And I like weird light on walls. And things that happen in and out of shadows. When it’s all about two people who love each other and you want to capture the spirit of that connection, you don’t really need to place them on an edge of a cliff with a technicolor sunset behind them. Sometimes the perfect black wall just seems right.

Birthdays sometimes feel like date markers of things that we should’ve done by now or a person we should’ve become by now, but it’s setting yourself up for a weird planned out life I think, if you look at it that way… And certainly early in my life and career, I always did. But on this birthday, I cut roses from a garden that I never dreamed I would own, I spent time with friends who have also become my family and I looked out at Thatcher and Emerson swimming in our pool and felt that the most interesting and exciting places to be are the places where you’re excited about the people in them. Even when it’s Jersey. 

This is me at 40 with my now first grader (!) in my bachelor button meadow that both bring me as many smiles as there are blooms. Thank you for making my birthday this week feel so special— I’m not sure about the number just yet but I know that these days I feel immensely loved and that is the greatest gift. 

#birthday #thisis40 #whatsnext #birthdaygirl

Spent the most luscious week in Puglia with some of my favorites.  There are certain humans that just have an effect on you where you ask yourself how you can make something better or more interesting or more visually compelling or how you can just push yourself to do something that feels unseen and ultimately creatively fulfilling. For the past decade of working together, I always think of @david_stark_design as being one of those gems of a visual storyteller who compels me to make some of my own best work, and in-kind I try to come to his events with uninhibited eyes. I’m excited to share what we came up with soon. 

And a sincere thank you to the gals @christinedlug and @kelseycowley who have become family and willingly follow me all over the world to make some of the most rich images, and to @benfinch for not crashing the drone in the Adriatic. Adore you kids.

Thank you @engagesummits for the most thrilling time in Paris— it was such a treat to hug old friends and meet new ones with Paris as the backdrop.  Rebecca and Kathryn have changed my life in so many ways and having this work family means everything. 

To the immensely talented photo team— each one of you made me so proud this week. 

And imagine my eyes when I found my dress matched the blue room at the Chateau — @wiederhoeft_ I just loved it— you made it feel so entirely me, thank you.

The fashion at weddings lately is making me reconsider how I shoot parts of the day in a lot of ways. I think there’s always so much focus on the couple, and rightfully, so, but there’s also a lot of story to be found with the guests. I’ve been carving out more time for guests portraits and finding it so fulfilling. The exchange is also I think what’s equally rewarding – the other weekend a guest thanked me for asking to make a portrait of her, that she had been feeling a little bit insecure lately, and that it made her feel so seen. I loved that, and ultimately think that’s what we offer when we make a photograph of someone. The opportunity for that person to feel seen.

My kiddos did a thing. Last Wednesday, Josh & Serena got married in New York on the perfect fall day – the kind of day that is a real sell for moving to the city. Cool air, bright skies. Blake bundled a bouquet of summer’s last clematis and we made the trip down to City Hall. A couple of stops along the way— found some of my light, and so much light in the two of them. This collection of photographs is a little bit of him, a little bit her, how I see two friends so dear to my heart. Meeting Josh and Serena has been one of the great gifts of my life. So many places we’ve been together… so many they will go now side by side. It was my sincere honor to witness and capture the start to their married love story.  All my love and congratulations. ♥️ @joshgoodencinema @thisdarlinglife

Alexandra and Stefan's welcome party seen in @voguemagazine at Palacio de Las Dueñas was truly a collaboration. The bride’s vision for a Kamayan-inspired Filipino feast was filled with lush tropical fruits and vibrant, exotic blooms. She requested a design and environment that was diverse, playful and filled with an abundance of color. The gorgeous, handmade dinner plates produced in Spain along with the linens and custom printed pieces brought this vision to life. The setting provided the dreamiest backdrop for this tropical wonderland. Dinner was served on huge banana leaves covering the surfaces of the rustic wooden tables. The incredibly delicious menu was prepared by Chef Jordy Navarra from Manila’s @toyoeatery known as the best restaurant in the Philippines. Matthew and Luis wanted to end the meal with something surprising for the bride and groom, so they presented the idea of featuring mango desserts by @cedricgrolet from @lemeuriceparis in Paris. His desserts are truly a work of art, and mango is the bride's favorite fruit, so it was the perfect detail to finish the celebration. The custom cocktails were flawlessly prepared by the talented @chopinvodka team and complimented the tropical vibe of the event. As guests departed, they were given a red carnation which is of course the national flower of Spain. It was a memorable evening filled with the spirit of Seville and the flavors and textures of the Philippines.

In her classic New York sort of way – a city of contradictions and complications and glamour and grit, a flood for the ages washed over downtown on Friday night and it seemed there would not be a glimmer of sunlight all day Saturday. And then the city surprised us at cocktail hour, and the sun peaked out. New York— she always keeps you on your toes.

Guests experienced J and J’s wedding on multiple floors of the downtown Manhattan venue, each elevator opening to reveal an unexpected and thrilling surprise— Between the art deco inspired ceremony space 66 flights up in the Observatory to a cocktail hour filled with food as visually striking as it was delicious alongside an original Basquiat painting, a candle lit reception that leaned into the atmosphere of the chicest New York restaurant, to an after party that overlooked the twinkling city lights— It was a feast for the senses.

To think about my childhood is to also hear the notes of Tchaikovsky in my head, to see legs in a tangle of pink ribbon on the floor of an old auditorium, satin, twisting and tying and fingers furiously darning pointe shoes. Everything about my life as a young girl went hand-in-hand with my life as a ballet dancer. Memories of my parents—dinners eaten at 10pm, my mother standing in the kitchen as I ate what she’d saved me after a late night rehearsal, furiously trying to finish my homework. Seeing my dad, a silhouette, always standing in the back, sneaking out before the curtain closed, but always there. He would give me a geode or a fossil after each performance, not the typical roses, and it makes me smile to think of what he would have thought of Emerson, my tiny paleontologist. They would have been best of friends. 

Today Emerson performs in his first Nutcracker, with the wonderful @roxeyballet and I am full of emotion— he’s going through the motions of a six year old, he doesn’t really know this world yet, a bit of a reluctant party boy— but in the past couple of weeks of final dress rehearsals and load into the theater, I think he’s starting to see why I loved it. The feeling you get in your stomach in the wings and the friendships and experiences that will one day remind you of another version of yourself.  There isn’t a day that I don’t use some part of what I learned in ballet. I’ll be cheering Emerson and all the dancers on to today. With gratitude for Emerson’s director and teacher Melissa and Mark Roxey and for my teachers Madame Porter and Bridget who I think of often— this is a special day. 
Merde Emerson.
